ven if illegitimacy is recognised, no protocol mechanism exists to remedy it.", :stakeholder-impact "Illegitimacy is observable but not actionable."} #:concept{:failure-id :failure/binary-pass-overclaim, :failure-name "Binary-pass overclaim", :failure-summary "A benchmark reports pass/fail but implies broader correctness than the scenario coverage supports.", :stakeholder-impact "A reviewer may trust a result more than the evidence warrants."} #:concept{:failure-id :failure/evidence-rich-coverage-poor, :failure-name "Evidence-rich but coverage-poor", :failure-summary "The artifacts are strong but the tested scenarios are narrow, leaving edge cases unexercised.", :stakeholder-impact "A passing result may not generalise to untested configurations or adversarial conditions."} #:concept{:failure-id :failure/attested-but-unverified, :failure-name "Attested but unverified", :failure-summary "A result is signed or anchored but its semantic correctness has not been independently checked.", :stakeholder-impact "An attested result may be accepted as true when the underlying computation or scenario is flawed."} #:concept{:failure-id :failure/configuration-drift, :failure-name "Configuration drift", :failure-summary "A benchmark or scenario result is compared against another result produced under different settings, but the differences are not detected or recorded.", :stakeholder-impact "Invalid comparisons; incorrect conclusions about protocol regressions or improvements."} #:concept{:failure-id :failure/implicit-configuration, :failure-name "Implicit configuration", :failure-summary "A result depends on settings not recorded in the artifacts, making it unreproducible.", :stakeholder-impact "Another party cannot reproduce the result without reverse-engineering the implicit settings."} #:concept{:failure-id :failure/configuration-overclaim, :failure-name "Configuration overclaim", :failure-summary "A result is presented as general when it only holds under a narrow or unrepresentative configuration.", :stakeholder-impact "A reviewer may apply a result outside its valid configuration scope."} #:concept{:failure-id :failure/stale-configuration, :failure-name "Stale configuration", :failure-summary "A configuration hash or metadata points to settings that no longer match the executed scenario due to software changes or data migration.", :stakeholder-impact "Replayed results may differ non-deterministically from the original run."}], :concept/summaries [#:concept{:assumptions ["A buyer and merchant are identifiable protocol actors." "The escrow balance represents the payment amount." "Concept labels do not change protocol validity."], :id :ecommerce/purchase, :name "Ecommerce purchase", :out-of-scope ["Real-world shipping, delivery logistics, or product quality." "Chargebacks, fraud detection, or payment card networks." "Dispute resolution outside the protocol (courts, arbitration)."], :stakeholder-question "Can a marketplace payment flow remain fair when buyers, merchants,\n  resolvers, or governance behave strategically?", :summary "A buyer pays a merchant through escrow. Funds are released, refunded,\n  disputed, or locked depending on delivery, evidence, and resolver decisions."} #:concept{:assumptions ["A condition is defined at deposit creation and is evaluable." "The condition authority is either a resolver module or an oracle." "Concept labels do not change protocol validity."], :id :event/deposit, :name "Event deposit", :out-of-scope ["Real-world legal or contractual conditions." "Oracle quality, liveness, or security." "Multi-step conditional logic or dependent conditions."], :stakeholder-question "Can an escrowed deposit be released only when predefined conditions\n  are objectively met, and returned if they are not?", :summary "A depositor commits funds subject to a condition. Funds are released\n  to a beneficiary when the condition is met, or returned to the depositor\n  if the condition expires or fails. A condition authority verifies\n  whether the condition was satisfied."} #:concept{:assumptions ["Yield accrual is deterministic and reproducible from world state." "Yield modules have known, bounded risk profiles." "Held balances are observable from protocol state before allocation." "Concept labels do not change protocol validity."], :id :yield/yield-bearing, :name "Yield-bearing position", :out-of-scope ["Real-world APY, APR, or investment returns." "Market risk, impermanent loss, or oracle price deviations." "Tax treatment of yield as income or capital gain."], :stakeholder-question "Can my yield-bearing position be trusted to preserve its value, and what\n  happens if the protocol cannot cover all positions' principal plus\n  accrued yield?", :summary "A yield-bearing position holds principal that generates yield over time\n  according to a yield module (e.g. AAVE-like lending, fixed-rate). The\n  protocol tracks each position's principal, realized yield, and shortfall\n  status, and checks that held balances are sufficient to cover all active\n  positions."} #:concept{:assumptions ["Decision authority is resolvable from protocol state." "A resolver is the default authority unless governance, module, or rule intervenes." "Concept labels do not change protocol validity."], :id :consensus/authority, :name "Consensus authority", :out-of-scope ["Real-world legal authority or jurisdiction." "Off-chain identity of the resolver." "Social or reputation-based notion of authority."], :stakeholder-question "Was the entity that decided this outcome independent, authorised, and\n  free from capture or conflict of interest?", :summary "Who has the power to decide a contested outcome? Authority may be\n  vested in a specific resolver, a resolution module, governance, or\n  a default rule. Independence of the decision-maker determines whether\n  the outcome can be trusted."} #:concept{:assumptions ["Evidence is modelled as protocol events with timestamps and content hashes." "Deadlines are protocol-level parameters, not real-world legal deadlines." "Concept labels do not change protocol validity."], :id :consensus/evidence, :name "Consensus evidence", :out-of-scope ["Real-world evidentiary standards or rules of procedure." "Weight or credibility of individual evidence items." "Forensic analysis of evidence content."], :stakeholder-question "Did the decider have access to sufficient, timely, and relevant evidence\n  to reach an informed decision?", :summary "What facts were available to the decision process? Evidence may be\n  submitted, missing, contradictory, late, or ignored. The quality and\n  completeness of evidence determines whether the decision can be\n  considered informed."} #:concept{:assumptions ["Legitimacy is a composite concept derived from the other five consensus dimensions." "Strong scores on all five dimensions imply legitimacy." "Concept labels do not change protocol validity."], :id :consensus/legitimacy, :name "Consensus legitimacy", :out-of-scope ["Real-world political or social legitimacy." "Normative or ethical judgments about the outcome." "Acceptance by parties who always reject any adverse outcome."], :stakeholder-question "Should I accept this outcome as binding, or are there grounds —\n  procedural, evidentiary, or authority-based — to challenge it?", :summary "Why should parties accept the outcome as binding? Legitimacy derives\n  from proper authority, fair process, adequate evidence, timely\n  resolution, and available escalation. Weak or failed legitimacy means\n  one or more of these dimensions was compromised."} #:concept{:assumptions ["Confidence is distinct from pass/fail. A claim can pass with low confidence if coverage is thin. A claim can fail with high confidence if the failure is deterministic and well evidenced." "Confidence is dimensional, not scalar. Evidence confidence, coverage confidence, determinism confidence, and attestation confidence should be reported separately before any aggregate label is derived."], :id :concept/confidence, :name "Confidence", :out-of-scope ["This concept does not define a minimum confidence threshold for protocol acceptance." "This concept does not assign trust scores to individual actors or oracles." "This concept does not address statistical or Bayesian confidence intervals."], :stakeholder-question "How strongly is this result supported?", :summary "The strength of support for a result or claim, distinct from pass/fail status."} #:concept{:assumptions ["A result is valid only under the configuration that produced it. Claims of general protocol safety must be qualified by the configuration space explored." "Configuration includes protocol parameters, module selections, benchmark definitions, execution options, and temporal assumptions." "Configuration should be explicitly hashed and recorded in the artifact registry for every run that produces a claim result."], :id :concept/configuration, :name "Configuration", :out-of-scope ["This concept does not prescribe which configuration parameters should be varied in a sensitivity analysis." "This concept does not define a canonical configuration for production deployment." "This concept does not address environmental configuration outside the protocol and execution layers (e.g., hardware, OS, network)."], :stakeholder-question "Under what conditions does this result hold?", :summary "The explicit settings under which a scenario, benchmark, or claim result is valid."} #:concept{:assumptions [], :failure-modes [:failure/unmodelled-sink :failure/unmodelled-source :failure/double-counted-liability :failure/false-conservation-failure :failure/rounding-dust-unaccounted :failure/wrong-claimant-allocation :failure/hidden-shortfall :failure/stale-claimable-after-cancel], :id :robustness/protocol-value-conservation, :maps-to {:benchmark-domain :domain/protocol-value-conservation, :claims [:claim/funds-conserved :claim/slashing-conservation :claim/no-leakage-beyond-shortfall :claim/partial-fill-fairness :claim/yield-preserved-during-shortfall :claim/appeal-bond-adequacy :claim/no-over-slashing :claim/solvency-status], :evidence [:evidence/world-before :evidence/world-after :evidence/state-diff :evidence/claimable-classification :evidence/allocation-result :evidence/invariant-result :evidence/trace], :framework-concepts [:concept/conservation], :scenarios ["settlement release/refund scenarios" "yield shortfall scenarios" "partial-fill withdrawal scenarios" "resolver slashing scenarios" "appeal and bond custody scenarios" "cancellation/finality scenarios"]}, :name "Protocol value conservation and allocation", :out-of-scope [], :stakeholder-language "When value moves through the protocol, every unit should be explainable:\n    paid out, refunded, held, slashed, assigned as a fee, recorded as a\n    shortfall, deferred as a recognised claim, waived by rule, or tracked as\n    bounded residual dust. The benchmark should make it clear where value\n    went and whether the distribution followed the intended rule.", :stakeholder-question "When value moves through the protocol, every unit should be explainable:\n    paid out, refunded, held, slashed, assigned as a fee, recorded as a\n    shortfall, deferred as a recognised claim, waived by rule, or tracked as\n    bounded residual dust. The benchmark should make it clear where value\n    went and whether the distribution followed the intended rule.", :summary "Whether protocol value is fully accounted for, correctly classified,\n    and distributed according to explicit protocol rules across settlement,\n    yield, bonds, slashing, fees, shortfalls, deferred claims, residuals,\n    and cancellation paths.", :title "Protocol value conservation and allocation", :why-it-matters "Most serious protocol failures are value-accounting failures: value can\n    disappear, appear without a source, be counted twice, be assigned to the\n    wrong bucket, or be hidden as an implicit shortfall. This benchmark\n    dimension gives reviewers a direct way to inspect whether Sew's\n    value-moving mechanisms remain auditable under ordinary, adversarial,\n    and shortfall conditions."}]}, :evidence/hash "c89314489c91d046a6bdad7a4971902dc81f1b44870495220aea1b709dcdc125", :run/manifest {:adapter "class resolver_sim.benchmark.runner.SewAdapter", :declared-run-count 1, :execution-count 15, :metrics {:declared-run-count 1, :execution-count 15, :passed 6, :passed-execution-count 6, :total 15, :unique-scenario-count 15}, :scenario-count 15, :scenario-hashes [{:file "resource:scenarios/edn/S78_yield-aave-partial-liquidity-release.edn", :outcome :pass, :benchmark/run-count 1, :benchmark/run-index 1, :scenario/evidence-root "4cb790b99bbb34141f9d4ffc77e9548267ac7284594544667472b37b52d7e3cc", :scenario/id nil} {:file "resource:scenarios/edn/S78_yield-negative-yield-release-path.edn", :outcome :fail, :benchmark/run-count 1, :benchmark/run-index 1, :scenario/evidence-root "bf9a871d9b3a2874dfe6fa619ff33c624ab9cea71a556daa66dfe73591b4cc0a", :scenario/id nil} {:file "resource:scenarios/edn/S79_yield-aave-partial-liquidity-dispute-resolution.edn", :outcome :pass, :benchmark/run-count 1, :benchmark/run-index 1, :scenario/evidence-root "b1367922fa2d2818e12bd6bfd68f1c1b6ba6d751efcb3be5c7b09b7456a53b88", :scenario/id nil} {:file "resource:scenarios/edn/S79_yield-negative-yield-dispute-refund-path.edn", :outcome :fail, :benchmark/run-count 1, :benchmark/run-index 1, :scenario/evidence-root "c5da366d941b01f3ad6dc9f07035b1773033ed46f6ca59887314744ec5710cba", :scenario/id nil} {:file "resource:scenarios/edn/S80_yield-mostly-liquid-partial-liquidity.edn", :outcome :pass, :benchmark/run-count 1, :benchmark/run-index 1, :scenario/evidence-root "4cb790b99bbb34141f9d4ffc77e9548267ac7284594544667472b37b52d7e3cc", :scenario/id nil} {:file "resource:scenarios/edn/S80_yield-aave-partial-liquidity-governance-disable-post-create.edn", :outcome :pass, :benchmark/run-count 1, :benchmark/run-index 1, :scenario/evidence-root "4cb790b99bbb34141f9d4ffc